'You're seeing that the consumer is taking a healthier look and having more alternatives [than soda], such as tea, and coconut water,' Thomas Mullarkey, an analyst from Morningstar, told The Atlantic. 'But also, Americans have aged, and soft drinks are most popular among teenagers and twentysomethings.'

The biggest drop in beer was among young Americans and non-whites - the two fastest-growing demographics of US society.

According to the report, young adult drinkers' alcoholic drink preferences have changed dramatically over the past two decades.

